{\"video_title\":\"Template Pattern\",\"transcript\":\"вЂ‹Getting a large language models output in вЂ‹exactly the format that we вЂ‹want can be a challenge sometimes. вЂ‹The next pattern that I'm going to teach you about вЂ‹is going to help you get exactly the format вЂ‹you're looking for and tell ChatGPT where вЂ‹you want the information вЂ‹that it's producing put into the format. вЂ‹You're basically going to give it a template and вЂ‹then ChatGPT is going to go and fill in your template. вЂ‹Just like you might do with вЂ‹an assistant where you'd say here's the template that I вЂ‹use for creating these form letters and here are вЂ‹my different placeholders within my template вЂ‹and then your assistant could go вЂ‹in and fill in that template. вЂ‹That's exactly what we can do with the template pattern. вЂ‹The idea behind this pattern is we would like вЂ‹a specific template followed for our output, вЂ‹and we can describe that template to вЂ‹ChatGPT and then have it вЂ‹produce all of its output using that template. вЂ‹Now, we could do this with other approaches like вЂ‹few-shot examples but we're going to do вЂ‹this with the template pattern in this example. вЂ‹Here's what the template pattern looks like. вЂ‹We say, I'm going to give you a template for your output. вЂ‹We're queuing the large language model that вЂ‹there is a template that's going to be вЂ‹in play and it needs to follow it. вЂ‹Capitalized words are my placeholders, вЂ‹so we're telling it when you look at the template, вЂ‹if something is capitalized, вЂ‹that's something that you're going to вЂ‹replace with the content that you're generating. вЂ‹Fill in my placeholders with your output, вЂ‹so there's our queue to it to вЂ‹go and replace the placeholders, вЂ‹and please preserve вЂ‹the overall formatting of my template. вЂ‹We don't want ChatGPT to just вЂ‹decide on its own what the format should вЂ‹be and ignore everything вЂ‹that we're giving it in terms of instructions. вЂ‹Then I say my template is, вЂ‹and I've got this funky little template down here, вЂ‹and I'm going to talk through it. вЂ‹I have question with вЂ‹three asterisk in front вЂ‹of it and then three asterisk following it. вЂ‹Now, what this is going to do actually вЂ‹is this is using some knowledge of how вЂ‹ChatGPT in the ChatGPT interface вЂ‹formats the information that we see, вЂ‹so those three asterisks you are basically going to meet. вЂ‹You're going to italicize and bold, вЂ‹this is like a heading. вЂ‹It's going to say question and it's going to be вЂ‹in italics and it's going to be in bold. вЂ‹Then we want it to fill in a question, вЂ‹so question which is an all caps. вЂ‹Notice we're differentiating вЂ‹between things that are part of вЂ‹my template and things that are capitalized, вЂ‹which are things that are вЂ‹placeholders that it's going to fill in. вЂ‹Then we're saying answer, similarly, вЂ‹it's going to be in italics and bold. вЂ‹If you want to figure out how this works, вЂ‹this is called Markdown, вЂ‹so basically, ChatGPT is вЂ‹rendering the output to you in Markdown. вЂ‹I'm just using this knowledge вЂ‹to help me out a little bit. вЂ‹I'm creating a template that includes вЂ‹Markdown and then we're using a placeholder for answer. вЂ‹Now, you can guess I'm going to have вЂ‹it generate questions and answers, вЂ‹this is what's going to come next. вЂ‹But right now I'm just telling вЂ‹it what the template looks like. вЂ‹Here's what my template is going to вЂ‹be and I'm going to ask you to fill it in. вЂ‹Then I tell it, I will give you вЂ‹the data to format in the next prompt, вЂ‹create 20 questions using my template. вЂ‹Of course, it says it's happy to do that. вЂ‹Then what I did is I pasted in, вЂ‹from Wikipedia, an article on Paleo-Indians. вЂ‹My son was studying Paleo-Indians at school, вЂ‹and so I thought it would be fun. вЂ‹Can I generate some questions about Paleo-Indians for him вЂ‹and see if he can answer them or learn more, вЂ‹and it might be interesting вЂ‹to talk about these questions. вЂ‹I paste that in and then what we see is we get вЂ‹output that follows the template that we gave it. вЂ‹If you remember, the first thing вЂ‹was question and it was not in caps, вЂ‹so this was something we wanted it to preserve, вЂ‹and then we had question in all caps, вЂ‹and ChatGPT has generated вЂ‹a question about the Paleo-Indians, вЂ‹who were the Paleo-Indians? вЂ‹Now, interestingly, it has decided to put this in вЂ‹all caps too which actually works for the format, вЂ‹I didn't actually mean вЂ‹for it to put it in all caps, but it works. вЂ‹Then I had answer which was not capitalized, вЂ‹and then I had answer was something to be вЂ‹filled in that was an all caps, вЂ‹and it fills in the answers. вЂ‹It's creating questions about Paleo-Indians, вЂ‹who were the Paleo-Indians, вЂ‹and then it's filling in the answer to the question. вЂ‹But the whole thing is structured using my template. вЂ‹I told it generate 20 of these questions, вЂ‹and so it's basically repeated my template 20 вЂ‹different time but filling in the content. вЂ‹Now, notice these are really powerful placeholders. вЂ‹The placeholder I gave it was question, вЂ‹and so it has to understand what is вЂ‹the meaning of the word question. вЂ‹It looks at and has to understand to some degree, вЂ‹and people may argue it's not really вЂ‹understanding anything, it's doing something else. вЂ‹I'm going to talk about it in terms of understanding вЂ‹because I think that's a natural way to talk about it. вЂ‹If we later discover it doesn't вЂ‹really understand, it doesn't matter, вЂ‹the template pattern is a great way of using вЂ‹this and it's easier to вЂ‹talk about it in terms of understanding. вЂ‹It's understanding the placeholder вЂ‹that it means question, вЂ‹that your question that you generate should go here. вЂ‹Then it's understanding answer, вЂ‹answer is where the answer to the question should go. вЂ‹It knows, from my prompt, вЂ‹that it's supposed to generate 20 of вЂ‹these questions based on the content I'm g